prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: First reference band measurement
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We observe the comet's thermal continuum for the first time in band 7.

prj:TemporalParameters.prj:note:
Observations must occur by June 21 due to the proximity of the comet. After June 21, the comet is too far away. Note that observations in the 10 days before June 1, i.e. the 10 days before the nominal start of Cycle 2, would be fine!
The 7 science goals must be observed in a sequence that minimizes gaps. The order should be: "First reference band measurement" "Band 9 measurement" "Second reference band measurement" "Band 3 measurement" "Third reference band measurement" "Band 4 measurement" "Fourth reference band measurement"

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The Target Comet.
Comet 209P/LINEAR was discovered in February 2004 as asteroid 2004 CB. More detailed observations in late March 2004 revealed the object's cometary nature, showing extended emission from dust. These observations show that the comet is only very weakly active, however. The comet was recovered in late 2008 and then given the permanent designation 209P. It was seen on its current orbit in September 2013, so the ephemeris for the comet is now well established.
The comet will pass only 0.0555 AU from Earth on UT May 29, and stay fairly close to Earth for a few weeks, affording us an opportunity to study it up-close during the early part of ALMA's Cycle 2. The comet will not be particularly bright at visible-wavelengths -- about 12th magnitude -- but its proximity certainly helps.
Our primary observational goal is to detect 209P's nucleus. We expect to see a point-source; the low activity of the comet suggests that we are unlikely to see any of the dust coma at submm- and mm-wavelengths. Nonetheless, the wider the ALMA configuration, the better the resolution and the more likely we are to be able to tell if there is any coma contaminating the image. Additionally, if there is coma, the wider configuration will make it easier to make use of the coma to constrain properties of the dust, as described in the science case. Therefore we prefer a wide configuration, such as: C34-6, C34-5, C34-4, or C34-3. We would not use C34-7 since we require Band 9 data.
Estimated Flux Density and Timing.
The standard way to predict nucleus fluxes is to use a 2-D thermal model called 'NEATM' (Near-Earth Asteroid Thermal Model; Harris 1998). It was developed for asteroids but is applicable to cometary nuclei that are weakly active. In simple terms, the model divides up the nucleus into facets and calculates a temperature for each facet based on the Sun's position and an assumed thermal conductivity. Then it uses the Planck function to figure out the emission from each facet, and does the surface integral to derive the total flux density we would see from the entire, unresolved nucleus.
We show in Figure 1 the predicted flux density over time in the four frequencies (one each in Bands 9, 7, 4, and 3) that we are requesting here. We assumed the thermal conductivity was basically negligible. There are two curves for each frequency because we assumed two values for the nucleus's radius -- 0.8 km and 0.6 km. The radius is unknown at the moment but this is a good guess for an othe rwise intrinsically-faint comet (cf. Fernandez et al. 2013). The radius will be constrained by visible, IR, and potentially radar observations during the apparition, so we expect to have this crucial parameter in hand for our analysis once the data are obtained.
Note that the NEATM is a simple model and does not account for temperature depression at depths; it assumes the temperature of the surface is valid. However the curves representing the smaller assumed radius would also be valid for a 0.8-km nucleus that has a ~40% lower temperature or a lower emissivity. Thus the curves give a good sense of the fluxes we expect to measure.
We request that observations happen as close to June 1 as possible. Figure 1 shows that the nucleus would be brightest in the last week of May, but since that is outside of Cycle 2, we request time in the first two weeks of June. The last week of May would be acceptable also if that is logistically possible. The third week of June is acceptable but not nearly as favorable; the plots in Figure 1 show how rapidly the nucleus's brightness decreases. Dates after the third week of June are unacceptable.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Requested Frequencies and Sensitivities.
We request time to achieve sensitivities of 0.017 mJy at 112 GHz in Band 3, 0.025 mJy at 162 GHz in Band 4, 0.10 mJy at 307 GHz in Band 7, 0.33 mJy at 671 GHz in Band 9. The frequencies were determined by using our model fluxes and the OT to determine what frequencies within a band would take the least amount of time to achieve these sensitivities. We justify the sensitivities themselves below.
Since we are going for absolute photometry, we are constrained by the absolute calibration. The technical handbook (Doc 2.3, v1.1, sec. 10.2.7) says that such calibration will only be good to 20% in Band 9, 10% in Band 7, and 5% in Bands 3 and 4. Therefore we only request enough time to achieve enough S/N in the raw photometry such that the absolute calibration is the dominant contributor to the error budget. Therefore our observational goal is to achieve S/N=30 in Bands 7 and 9, S/N=20 in Band 4, and S/N=15 in Band 3. Note that since Band 3 is our faintest band, we make a compromise in the desired S/N; this is also why we want to have both Band 3 and Band 4 observations.
To derive a sensitivity for each band, we used Figure 1, using a pessimistic scenario where the observations occur on June 17. To find the sensitivity, we simply divided the flux by the required S/N. Note that if we are able to observe earlier in June, we will not need as much integration time since the nucleus will be brighter.
Including the calibration error, we expect to end up with S/N~4.9 in Band 9, S/N~9.5 in Band 7, S/N~14 in Band 4, and S/N~12 in Band 3. This is adequate for our needs, as we show in Figure 2. First, note the diamonds; these are the fluxes from June 17 in Figure 1. The solid line marks a Rayleigh-Jeans law fit to lead the eye. If these were our measured photometry, and by knowing the radius of the nucleus, we could extract the temperature from the overall scale of the flux (of course obviously not from the spectral slope for an R-J law).
Next, note the circles in Figure 2. The error bars are the same as for the diamonds, but here we have suppressed the fluxes by 30%, as if the brightness temperature had dropped by that amount. If these were our measured photometry, we would be able to tell that the temperature at mm-depth is lower than the surface temperature, i.e. that we have sampled a cooler layer.
Lastly, note the squares in Figure 2. Here we have assumed that emissivity or temperature has an empirical trend with inverse wavelength. If these were our measured photometry, we would be able to tell that there was a temperature or emissivity trend with depth. Depending on the actual slope of the line, we may alternately be able to constrain the actual temperature gradient, probably the most exciting result possible.
In short, the low S/N of absolutely-calibrated photometry is not a hindrance to our achieving our science goals since we would have such a long lever-arm in frequency.
Nucleus Rotational Context.
Cometary nuclei are elongated objects that spin; hence they show a variable cross section to an observer over time. Comet 209P's spin state is not known; for this reason, observations where each wavelength is separated widely in time (hours or longer) would be uninterpretable. Therefore our proposed observations must occur all consecutively as one scheduling block.
Furthermore, since the comet would likely rotate significantly as we observed from band to band, we need rotational context. Therefore we must observe the comet in one of the bands multiple times so we know how to interpret the results in the other two bands. We have chosen Band 7 to be this band since it gets us the best S/N in the shortest time. We bracket the Band 3, 4, and 9 observations with Band 7 shots.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to observe the submm- and mm-wave thermal emission from the nucleus and dust of comet 209P/LINEAR as it passes only 0.06 AU from Earth in June 2014. The comet presents a rare opportunity to sample the interior thermal properties of a cometary nucleus as a way to understand the source of cometary activity. We can also constrain the large-grain dust size distribution and thus the true mass loss from the comet.
